The Final Project is graded with a 10 point scale, and counts for 60% of the Practical Grade. There is no minimum grade for the Final Project, but the Practical Grade needs to be at least 5.0 to pass the course.

The points are distributed between standard and extra features. The standard features amount to 18 points. The extra features amount to 14 points, and you can also propose implementing further extra features by sending a respective email to cg-cs-ewi@tudelft.nl so that it can be approved by the organizers (you will receive a confirmation mail whether we accept the feature within two days). The final sum of points translates directly to your project grade, capped to a maximum of 10 points. Your code for the standard features is graded by testing the functions you implement on various inputs. The number of points you receive for a task is based on the percentage of correct cases and a weighting of the respective complexity of tasks. For the extra features, grading is performed manually. You will receive a breakdown of your grade in the feedback section on Brightspace.

Framework information

In this project, you will build upon fundamentals that you learned in the lecture and implemented in the assignments to develop a fully functional ray tracer. We provide a ray tracer framework, where you have to fill in the important parts. This chapter discusses some details of this framework.

The frameworks UI enables you to choose from a selection of test scenes to work with, including a custom scene (this initially loads a scene custom.obj from the data folder). If you like to load your own scene, you can simply overwrite the corresponding custom.obj with your own (please note that you should not rename your obj material file (.mtl), as the original filename is mentioned within the obj file itself).

On BVHInterface, HitInfo, Features, RenderState, and Sampler

The framework is similar to the code you worked with during the Ray Intersection Assignment. However, there are several common method arguments and structs which you should familiarize yourself with, as these store important information during rendering. These are:

  • BVHInterface, defined in bvh_interface.h, describes an acceleration structure to which your own acceleration structure implementation must conform. During grading, we test your implementation against this interface, and it is used throughout the framework to abstract away your implementation. BVHInterface allows you to run intersection tests against the entire scene, and returns information about ray hits in a HitInfo object.
  • HitInfo, defined in common.h, is returned by the various intersection tests, and stores information about a (potential) intersection point. This information is necessary for e.g.shading, texture lookups, and other material interactions. See Appendix A - Materials for details on materials.
  • Features/ExtraFeatures, defined in common.h, describe booleans to enable/disable features of the renderer on the fly. Each standard/extra feature you implement has a corresponding boolean here, and is accessible through the UI. Do not tamper with these booleans, as we use them during grading to isolate features. For example, we may disable the BVH when grading non-BVH-related features. You are free to extend the ExtraFeatures object with your own parameters.
  • RenderState, defined in render.h, holds handles to Scene, Features and a BVHInterface object. A RenderState is created per render thread at the start of rendering, and allows you to access these objects, as it is passed to most methods you implement. RenderState also holds a per-thread Sampler object, so you can generate random numbers in a thread-safe manner.
  • Sampler, defined in sampler.h , is generated per render thread, and is a fast, well-distributed pseudo-random number generator. This allows you to generate uniformly distributed, 1D/2D random numbers. You should use this when necessary; dont be that person still using rand().

Code Structure

Most of the frameworks components are separated into header/source files such that you can work on them in isolation. Here is an overview of which files relate to which ray tracer components that you should implement:

  • bvh.h/bvh.cpp - Your implementation of the acceleration structure, built on top of bvh_interface.h.
  • extra.h/extra.cpp - Your implementations of most optional extra features.
  • interpolate.h/interpolate.cpp - Your implementation of normal and other component interpolation.
  • light.h/light.cpp - Your implementations of light sampling features.
  • recursive.h/recursive.cpp - Your implementations of recursive ray tracing features.
  • render.h/render.cpp - Multithreaded rendering code, and your implementation of multisampling.
  • shading.h/shading.cpp - Basic shading models, and your implementation of Phong/Blinn-Phong models.
  • texture.h/texture.cpp - Your implementations of texture sampling features.

The following files you do not have to touch to solve the standard features, but you are encouraged to modify these to solve the extra features:

  • common.h - Basic data structures used throughout the application
  • main.cpp - The program launch point and the user interface.
  • draw.h/draw.cpp - Helper methods for visual debugging.
  • scene.h/scene.cpp - Responsible for loading the scene and auxiliary data.
  • intersect.h/intersect.cpp - The intersection tests you previously implemented. By default, the code in intersect.cpp is not used, and the framework links against a prebuilt reference solution. Refer to Compilation for details.
  • your_tests.cpp - Example unit tests that demonstrate the program interface. If left untouched, these should compile and pass for your implementation.

The following files were not described, but you must not modify these, as they will probably break grading tests: fwd.h, bvh_interface.h, sampler.h, config.h/config.cpp, screen.h/screen.cpp, verification.cpp. Be careful: if you break grading tests because you modified these files, your project will not receive points for your features. As a helpful tool, the file verification.cpp includes some assertions that tell you what component you may have modified, and the file your_tests.cpp shows how components may be used in grading tests.

Compilation

As previously stated, we provide a prebuilt library for the required Windows environment with the reference solutions for the intersection functions, hence the intersect.h and intersect.cpp files are not used by default. If, instead, you wish to use your own functions, you can use these files and add the following argument to CMAKE: -DUSE_PREBUILT_INTERSECT=OFF. In this case, the prebuilt library will be ignored. We have also included binaries for Mac and Linux but we cannot guarantee they will work with your compiler and OS version (you might need to use the solution without the prebuilt binaries in this case).

To start, you can compile the code and test the application. Note that you can compile the code in at least two different modes DEBUG or RELEASE. When compiled in DEBUG mode, there are a lot of additional tests behind the scenes, e.g., if you are accessing a std::vector, it always checks that you stay within its bounds. It is very useful to compile in DEBUG mode when developing code to ensure that all these tests are performed. Nevertheless, once the code is working, you should switch to RELEASE. If you now compile the code, it will be optimized and result in a significant speedup. Especially when working with complicated scenes, it is a good idea to rely on RELEASE mode. In the same spirit, when in DEBUG mode, you should rather work with simpler scenes to avoid long render times. Whichever mode you chose, once compiled, you should be able to launch the application.

On our side, we use MSVC on Windows to compile your project and run tests. With this in mind, you should not use any external libraries (except for the included intersect.lib). If you do (and frankly, you shouldnt have to), please make sure that your project can be compiled without any extra efforts, or it might affect the grading.

Rasterization Mode

From the menu, you can choose a Rasterization and a Ray tracing view mode. The OpenGL-based Rasterization mode serves for debugging and scene control.

The GUI allows you to insert, remove and otherwise modify light sources, which are only used during Ray traced mode. This means the illumination in Rasterization mode does not correspond to the illumination in Ray traced mode. During Rasterization, we just consider a single light source in the scene to add some illumination.

Visual debugging features are only enabled during the Rasterization mode. See Visual Debugging for more information.

Ray Traced Mode

During the Ray traced mode, the program generates at least one camera ray per pixel. This is bootstrapped by the renderImage() method in render.h/render.cpp. For each camera ray, the renderRay() method in recursive.h/recursive.cpp is called, which computes an RGB color value by determining the light along that ray towards the cameras pixel. The renderRay() method calls other methods such that reflections, shadows, and other effects are taken into account. We recommend you read both methods to understand them, but you should not have to modify these in your implementation.

While the Ray traced mode traces actual rays for each pixel, you can also click the Render to file button to render an image and save it to file directly. This functionality is available in the Rasterization mode, so you can render to a file without switching to Ray traced mode, if the latter is too slow. For simple scenes, the Ray traced mode may be interactive, but as scene and effect complexity increases, ray tracing performance will inevitably slow to a halt. To alleviate this, you will be asked to create an acceleration data-structure as part of the standard features.

Rendering the Cornell Box without any features enabled should result in the following image. If you are using the prebuilt intersect library, you should be able to reproduce this result just by running the program before altering any code.

When a scene is loaded, it is centered and scaled according to the longest axis. Hereby, the placing of the light sources in the scene via the interface is facilitated. Via the interface, you can add light sources, change their type/color or move them around.

Visual Debugging

For some features, you are expected to implement Visual Debugging tools. This is generally the element to start with, and it should aid in verifying the correctness of your implementation. By having visual feedback of calculations, you are able to catch bugs early on. Visual debugging can be implemented in the same methods as the rest of your code.

Below are some tips to help you:

  • When you press r in Rasterization mode, this generates and launches a single debug ray through the mouse cursor. By using drawRay() from draw.h/draw.cpp and other draw functions, you can and should expand this debug ray to illustrate how your ray progresses recursively through the scene. This allows you to inspect e.g.reflections, transparency, and visibility tests.
  • The UI library, Dear ImGui allows you to inject your own interfaces, toggles and sliders throughout the code. Dear ImGui makes it simple, so we recommend you use it for visual debugging.
  • Experiment with the debugging outputs. For example, you can color a ray to illustrate the current depth with respect to the number of reflections, or you can draw a line to illustrate the normal of each surfaces encountered by the ray.
  • For other features you will need other forms of visual debugging that are not based on drawing rays. You might notice quickly that tsuch visualizations are very useful when debugging your work. Refer to draw.h/draw.cpp for helper code.

Appendix A - General Remarks

Materials (.MTL)

OBJ files have an optional accompanying MTL file. When you create a model with materials in Blender, the MTL file is also exported together with the OBJ file. Note that some advanced material options in Blender are not supported by the MTL file format. The MTL files are automatically loaded by the framework, since the MTL filename is mentioned in the OBJ file. We have added a Material structure to the framework to allow easy access to material coefficients.

// Defined in framework/mesh.h
struct Material {
    glm::vec3 kd;
    glm::vec3 ks { 0.0f }; 
    float shininess { 1.0f };
    float transparency { 1.0f };

    // Pointer to optional diffuse texture
    std::shared_ptr<Image> kdTexture;
};

Diffuse coefficient. You can ignore the materials diffuse coefficeint and texture pointer. To access this coefficient, use the helper method, sampleMaterialKd() in the shading.h file, which forwards to the correct component.

glm::vec3 kd = sampleMaterialKd(state, hitInfo);

Transparency. We have added one additional parameter to the material, transparency, which ranges from 0.0 (fully transparent) to 1.0 (fully opaque). Note that, despite its name, this correspondings directly to the alpha component in alpha blending. This should be used for your implementation. In Blender you can set the transparency by going to the Material tab, activating transparency and setting the Alpha value. This value will be exported to the MTL file and imported by the framework.

Multiple materials. If you created a model that uses multiple materials, they will be automatically handled by splitting them into submeshes. The loadMesh method in mesh.cpp actually returns a vector of meshes, and not a single mesh, such that each submesh has its own material properties. Also note that the BVH structure represents the entire scene, and already loops over all submeshes for you. In the end, you can directly access its material object through the HitInfo object.

Drawing debug rays

A ray is defined by its origin, direction, and intersection parameter t, as defined in the Ray Intersection assignment. You can define your own rays for debugging and call the method drawRay from draw.h/draw.cpp to render it in Rasterization mode. This function also draws a small sphere at the intersection point, unless you do not modify the t value (it is set to infinity - i.e.FLOAT_MAX).

Here is an example of how to draw a green ray:

// Define an arbitrary ray and the color green
Ray ray = { .origin = glm::vec3(1, 0, 2), .direction = glm:vec3(0, 0, 1), .t = 3.0 };
glm::vec3 color (0, 1, 0);

// Call drawRay, declared in the `draw.h` file
drawRay(ray, color);

Drawing debug boxes

In the draw.h/draw.cpp file you can likewise find a method to draw axis-aligned bounding boxes (AABBs):

void drawAABB(const AxisAlignedBox& box, DrawMode drawMode, const glm::vec3& color, float transparency);

The draw mode can be either DrawMode::Filled to render the sides of the AABB, or DrawMode::Wireframe to render only the edges. You can also pass a color and transparency value. This last value can be used with DrawMode::Filled to draw transparent boxes, where 0.0 if fully transparent and 1.0 is fully opaque.

Appendix B - Standard Feature Descriptions

In this appendix, we provide detailed descriptions of the standard features mentioned previously. Descriptions involve (a) what the feature implementation entails, (b) where we expect or require you to implement the feature. Some features require you to implement a single method, other features comprise multiple methods.

Please note: the instructions here are requirements, not suggestions. Not following the requirements may lead to point subtraction as the automatic tests might fail. Further, methods sometimes provide more detailed in-code comments explaining how they should be approached; especially the acceleration structures buildRecursive(...) and intersectRayWithBVH methods.

Acceleration data structure

Flags: features.enableAccelStructure, files: bvh.h, bvh.cpp.

This is the most laborious part of the project and the requirement that will allow you to render large scenes in a reasonable amount of time. Youll implement a Bounding Volume Hierarchy (BVH). As bounding volumes, you will use Axis-Aligned Bounding Boxes (AABBs) as seen in the lecture, and a binary tree such that every parent node has two children.

Your BVH is implemented on top of an interface defined in bvh_interface.h. You are not allowed to modify this interface, but you should certainly read it! If you modify the interface, you will break grading tests. We recommend you understand how the interfaces Primitive and Node objects allow for a compact representation of the scenes meshes, as youll be interacting with them in your own implementation.

Methods

  • [0.25] - computePrimitiveAABB(...) - Given a BVH triangle, compute an axis-aligned bounding box around the primitive.
  • [0.25] - computeSpanAABB(...) - Given a range of BVH triangles, compute an axis-aligned bounding box around the range.
  • [0.25] - computePrimitiveCentroid(...) - Given a BVH triangle, compute the geometric centroid of the triangle.
  • [0.25] - computeAABBLongestAxis(...) - Given an AABB, return the longest axis as (x = 0, y = 1, z = 2).
  • [1.50] - splitPrimitivesByMedian(...) - Given a range of BVH triangles, sort these along a specified axis based on their geometric centroid. Then, find and return the split index in the range, such that the subrange containing the first element of the list is at least as big as the other, and both differ at most by one element in size.
  • [0.25] - bvh.buildLeafData(...) - Implement this helper method to instantiate Node objects as a leaf node. Implement this first, and reuse it in bvh.buildRecursive(...).
  • [0.25] - bvh.buildNodeData(...) - Implement this helper method to instantiate Node objects as a parent with two children. Implement this first, and reuse it in bvh.buildRecursive(...).
  • [1.00] - bvh.buildRecursive(...) - Hierarchy construction routine, called by the BVHs constructor; recursively create the BVH hierarchy.
  • [2.00] - intersectRayWithBVH(...) - Hierarchy traversal routine; called by the BVHs intersect(). Intersect a ray with the BVH and its primitives, and update HitInfo accordingly.

Visual debug

As visual debug, we recommend you (a) visualize one level of the BVHs hierarchy at a time by drawing the hierarchys respective AABBs, and (b) visualize one leaf node at a time including its contained triangles. This can help you verify correctness to some extent. To facilitate this, you may want to implement the following methods:

  • bvh.buildNumLevels(...)/buildNumLeaves(...) - Helper functions to count the nr. of levels and leaves, called by the BVHs constructor. These should fill in m_numLevels/m_numLeaves. Use these for your performance report table as well.
  • bvh.debugDrawLevel(...)/debugDrawLeaf(...) - Draw bounding boxes or leaf data. These are controlled from the UI by default.

Example renders

Shading models

Flags: features.enableShading, features.shadingModel, files: shading.h, shading.cpp.

This feature partially repeats work from prior assignments, and requires you to implement a custom shading model. You must integrate your old Phong and Blinn-Phong models correctly into the ray tracer implementation, using HitInfo, Material, and other objects. By default, Lambertian shading is already implemented. Afterwards, you must implement a non-photorealistic model which instead evaluates a piecewise linear function - a gradient function - to determine surface color.

Methods

  • [0.00] - computePhongModel(...) - Given a camera direction, a light direction, a relevant intersection, and a color coming in from the light, evaluate the Phong Model returning the reflected light towards the target.

  • [0.00] - computeBlinnPhongModel(...) - Given a camera direction, a light direction, a relevant intersection, and a color coming in from the light, evaluate the Blinn-Phong Model returning the reflected light towards the target.

  • [0.50] - LinearGradient.sample(...) - Given a number ti between [-1, 1], sample from the gradients components and return the linearly interpolated color, for which ti lies in the interval between the t-values of two components, or on a boundary. If ti falls outside the gradients smallest/largest components, the nearest component must be sampled.

  • [0.50] - computeLinearGradientModel(...) - Given a camera direction, a light direction, a relevant intersection, and a color coming in from the light, evaluate a diffuse shading model, such that the diffuse component is sampled not from the intersected material, but a provided linear gradient, based on the cosine of theta.

Example renders

Recursive ray reflections

Flags: features.enableReflections, files: recursive.h, recursive.cpp, dependency: shading models.

This feature extends the method renderRay(...) to enable recursive specular reflections. Every time a ray intersects a specular surface (read, material.ks is non-zero), you should generate a mirror reflectance ray and evaluate its contribution.

Methods

  • [0.50] - generateReflectionRay(...) - Given an incident ray and a intersection point, generate a mirrored ray.
  • [0.50] - renderRaySpecularComponent(...) - Given a camera ray (or secondary ray) and an intersection, compute the contribution of a mirrored ray, by recursively evaluating renderRay(, depth + 1), and adding the result times material.ks to the current intersections hit color.

Visual debug

As visual debug, we recommend you visualize (a) the surface normal at the location where your ray reflects, and (b) visualize secondary rays with a different color.

Example renders

Recursive ray transparency

Flags: features.enableTransparency, files: recursive.h, recursive.cpp, dependency: shading models.

This feature extends the method renderRay(...) to enable recursive transparent passthrough. Every time a ray intersects a transparent surface (read, material.transparency is non-one), you should generate a passthrough ray, evaluate its contribution, and correctly alpha-blend results.

Methods

  • [0.50] - generatePassthroughRay(...) - Given an incident ray and a intersection point, generate a passthrough ray for transparency, starting at the intersection point and continuing in the same direction.
  • [0.50] - renderRayTransparentComponent(...) - Given a camera ray (or reflected camera ray) and an intersection, compute the contribution of a passthrough transparent ray, recursively evaluating renderRay(, depth + 1) along this ray, and correctly alpha blending the result with the current intersections hit color.

Visual debug

As visual debug, we recommend you (a) visualize passthrough rays using the blended color, and show properties of the intersected surface (transparency, kd).

Example renders

Interpolation

Flags: features.enableNormalInterp files: interpolate.h, interpolate.cpp.

This feature enables smooth shading of your models, which means you need to smoothly interpolate vertex data inside a ray-intersected triangle. Given the intersection in a triangle, youll compute the intersections barycentric coordinates and use these to generate the correct vertex data. Note that, currently, these methods are called from updateHitInfo(...) in the bvh.cpp file, if the corresponding flags are enabled.

Methods

  • [0.50] - computeBarycentricCoord(...) - Given three triangle vertices and a point on the triangle, compute the corresponding barycentric coordinates of the point and return a vec3 with the barycentric coordinates (alpha, beta, gamma).
  • [0.25] - interpolateNormal(...)/interpolateTexCoord(...) - Linearly interpolate three vertex normals/texture coordinates using barycentric coordinates. Make sure the output is valid with respect to the input.

Example renders

Texture mapping

Flags: features.enableTextureMapping, files: texture.h, texture.cpp, dependency: normal interpolation.

To give your rendered image that final look, you should support textures in the ray-tracer. Given texture coordinate data on the hitInfo object, you can perform texture lookups in a diffuse texture.

Methods

  • [0.50] - sampleTextureNearest(...) - Given an image and relevant texture coordinates, sample the texture s.t. the nearest texel to the coordinates is acquired from the image.
  • [1.00] - sampleTextureBilinear(...) - Given an image and relevant texture coordinates, sample the texture s.t. a bilinearly interpolated texel is acquired from the image.

Example renders

Lights and shadows

Flags: features.enableShadows, features.numShadowSamples, files: light.h, light.cpp, dependency: shading models.

In this feature, you will implement the contribution of lights and shadows. By default, the only light type that is supported is the point light as computeContributionPointLight(...) in light.cpp has a barebones implementation (which does not incorporate shadows). You will implement the following methods, and in doing so build towards a good setup for handling the three different light types (points, segments, and parallellograms) with both hard and soft shadows. We recommend that you implement them in the order given in this document.

Methods

  • [0.25] - sampleSegmentLight(...) - Given a single segment light, transform a uniformly distributed 1d sample in \([0, 1)\), into a uniformly sampled position and color on the segment light, and write these into the reference return values.
  • [0.25] - sampleParallelogramLight(...) - Given a single paralellogram light, transform a uniformly distributed 2d sample in \([0, 1),\) into a uniformly sampled position and color on the paralellogram light, and write these into the reference return values.
  • [1.50] - testVisibilityLightSampleBinary(...) - Given a sampled position on some light, and the emitted color at this position, return whether or not the light is visible from the provided ray/intersection.
  • [0.50] - computeContributionPointLight(...) - Given a single point light, compute its contribution towards an incident ray at an intersection point.
  • [0.50] - computeContributionSegmentLight(...)/computeContributionParallelogramLight(...) - Given a single segment/parallelogram light, compute its contribution towards an incident ray at an intersection point by integrating over the segment, taking numSamples samples.
  • [2.00] - testVisibilityLightSampleTransparency(...) - Given a sampled position on some light, and the emitted color at this position, return the light that is visible from the provided ray/intersection taking alpha-blending into account, or 0 if this is not the case. Use the following blending operation: lightColor = lightColor * kd * (1 - alpha). Please reflect within 50 words in your report on why this is incorrect, and illustrate two examples of what is incorrect.

Visual debug

As visual debug, we recommend you visualize visibility rays and whether or not these pass/fail. In addition, it is smart if you visualize the samples generated on your segment/parallelogram light, to verify they are uniformly distributed across the light.

Example renders

Multisampling

Flags: features.numPixelSamples, files: render.h, render.cpp.

Finally, to ensure that the image you render can be smoothly generated, you must handle multisampling, a form of anti-aliasing. While the ray-tracer by default renders pixels by sending a ray through the pixels center, you must now extend generatePixelRays() to support placement of multiple rays within a pixel. In addition, you must implement jittered sampling, where rays are randomly sampled from each cell in a grid across the pixel.

Methods

  • [0.75] - generatePixelRaysMultisampled(...) - Given a render state, camera, pixel position, and output resolution, generates a set of camera ray samples distributed uniformly across this pixel.
  • [1.00] - generatePixelRaysJittered(...) - Given a render state, camera, pixel position, and output resolution, generates a set of camera ray samples placed using jittered sampling throughout this pixel.

Example renders

Appendix C - Extra Feature Descriptions

In this appendix, we provide descriptions of the extra features mentioned previously. Unlike with the standard features, we do not specify exactly how or what or where to implement, but provide suggestions. For some features, we impose certain restrictions on what it should or should not be. These features can be implemented with the material from the lectures and the book (Fundamentals of Computer Graphics 4th Edition). If you deviate from these materials, justify why you made this choice (not guaranteed that you will get full points). Do not forget to cite your references!

We have made isolated placeholder methods available in extra.h/extra.cpp, within which you should be able to implement the extra feature. Note that you are given the freedom to diverge from these methods, but we simply recommend you use them. Mirroring the placeholder methods, placeholder feature flags are available in the ExtraFeatures struct in common.h. These are integrated into the UI and currently correctly toggle their respective placeholder methods.

If indicated, you should add some form of visual debugging to verify the correctness of your implementation, and include screenshots in the report. Explain how and why your visual debugger helps to verify the correctness of the result. You cannot just reuse a visual debug from other features, it should have something unique to support the feature in question. Again, as an example, SAH+Binning should have some new visual debug other than the default methods provided for the BVH Not implementing a visual debug may lead to only partial points being given during grading.

Environment maps

Given a camera ray (or reflected camera ray) that does not intersect the scene, evaluates the contribution along the ray, originating from an environment map. You may have to add support for environment maps to the Scene object, and provide or hardcode a scene with the right data for this.

Flags: features.extra.enableEnvironmentMap, methods: sampleEnvironmentMap(...), files: extra.h, extra.cpp.

Source. Refer to Lecture Ray Tracing and the book.

SAH+binning as splitting criterion for the BVH (+ visual debug) (+ performance row in report)

As an alternative to splitPrimitivesByMedian, use a SAH+binning splitting criterion. You should add a visual debug and show this in your report. Further, you should extend the performance table in your report with updated numbers.

Flags: features.extra.enableBvhSahBinning, methods: splitPrimitivesBySAHBin(...), files: extra.h, extra.cpp.

Source. Refer to Lecture Data Structures and the book.

Motion blur (+ visual debug)

Given the same input as for renderImage(), instead render an image with your own implementation of motion blur. Here, you integrate over a time domain, and not just the pixels image domain, allowing objects to move during a render, and visualize the appearance of movement. Here are some points to account for:

  • You should add a visual debug and show this in your report.
  • Your approach must involve ray-tracing. 2D or screen-space approaches are not accepted!
  • Your approach should moves one or more objects in a complicated pattern such as a spline, across the screen; do not simply move the camera or apply a linear transformation. This can integrate with visual debugging features.
  • Your approach should involve a sampling-based approach (where the time domain is sampled between keyframes of motion), as opposed to simply averaging several frames.

Flags: features.extra.enableMotionBlur, methods: renderImageWithMotionBlur(...), files: extra.h, extra.cpp.

Source. Refer to Lecture Ray Tracing and the book.

Bloom filter post-processing

Given a rendered image, compute and apply a bloom post-processing effect to add a glow to bright pixels.

  • As a filter, we want to use a 2D gaussian filter. To accelerate its application, we will use the fact that it is a separable filter, meaning that we can first filter the image horizontally, then the result vertically.
  • To define the filters values, apply the following: First, the \(n^{th}\) value in a 1D filter is defined as \(C(n,k)=\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}\), where \(k\) is the total number of pixels in the 1D filter. Then, you should divide all values by the total sum of all filter pixel values.

Flags: features.extra.enableBloomEffect, methods: postprocessImageWithBloom(...), files: extra.h, extra.cpp.

Source. Refer to Lecture Images.

Glossy reflections (+ visual debug)

Given a camera ray (or reflected camera ray) and an intersection, evaluates the contribution of a set of glossy reflective rays, recursively evaluating renderRay(..., depth + 1) along each ray, and adding the results times material.ks to the current intersections hit color. Here are some points to account for:

  • You should add a visual debug and show this in your report.
  • The book explains that you should construct an orthonormal basis along the ray, and sample on the quad formed by this basis. We expect you to instead sample on a disk, orthogonal to the ray. Sample the disk uniformly.
  • You should use the material shininess parameter to modulate how glossy the surface really looks. For example, modulate the size of the sampling disk, by resizing it over \(shinniess / 64\).

Flags: features.extra.enableGlossyReflection, features.extra.numGlossySamples, methods: renderRayGlossyComponent(...), files: extra.h, extra.cpp.

Source. Refer to the book.

Depth of Field (+ visual debug)

Given the same input as for renderImage(), instead render an image with your own implementation of depth of field. Here, you generate camera rays s.t. a focus point and a thin lens camera model are in play, allowing objects to be in and out of focus. Here are some points to account for:

  • You should add a visual debug and show this in your report. For example, allow your debug to control the focus point.
  • Your approach must involve camera ray generation. 2D or screen-space approaches are not accepted!
  • Your approach preferably samples rays from the pixel, similar to multisampling.

Flags: features.extra.enableDepthOfField, methods: renderImageWithDepthOfField(...), files: extra.h, extra.cpp.

Source. Refer to the book.
